<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-295-148  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 295 148.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 18 1989 n1164 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>That's the way the money goes. (changes in computing salaries)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Enticknap, Nicholas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An April 1989 survey of employment advertisements in the tradepress and national papers reveals that computing salaries onaverage rose less than inflation in 1988.andP;  The greatest advanceswere for telecommunications specialists.andP;  Salaries offered tosenior specialists in that field rose nearly 20 percent, whilenetwork controllers were offered 13.5 percent more and softwareengineers 10.6 percent more.andP;  In contrast, operators are beingoffered 8 percent more, systems analysts 7 percent more andprogrammers and analyst-programmers 4 percent more.andP;  Demand hasincreased for those experienced in local area networks, fourthgeneration languages, relational databases and designmethodologies.andP;  While clearly short of staff, employers are notprepared to raise salaries to overcome the shortage.andP;  The fullsurvey results may be ordered from an address listed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SalarySurveyOutlookComputer IndustryLabor Costs.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Annual percentage rise. (graph)National average salaries offered. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>